defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;defaultHearing loss and other long-term conditions in adefaultn ageing populationdefault3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnmet communication needs, arising from unmanaged hearing loss, pose a challenge to provision of care and hence the wider management of other long term conditions.
default 
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPeople with hearing loss experience greater difficulties in accessing health
default and social care
default services and
default public health information, and
default receive a lower standard of health service across the board.
default 
default3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUnmanaged hearing loss can bring about challenges in terms of the management of particular conditions such as diabetes, where patients can play a large role in self-managing their condition, 
defaultso
default effective communication with health professionals 
defaultis
default essential.
default3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultParticular psychological and behavioural challenges can result where people have unmanaged hearing loss alongside other conditions that c
defaultan cause additional 
defaultcommunication difficulties such as stroke, dementia, sight loss or Parkinson’s.
defaultImproving the defaultmanagement of defaultmultipledefault conditionsdefaultDesigning integrateddefault defaultservicesdefault defaultfor people with long-term conditionsdefault13.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGPs and all health professionals should be aware of the high prevalence of hearing loss and links between hearing loss and other long-term conditions. They should enquire about whether the person has a hearing loss, 
defaultcross-refer 
defaultand cooperate with other professionals.
default13.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultO
defaultpportunistic and targeted hearing checks 
defaultshould be integrated 
defaultinto other services and settings, such as in pharmacies, care homes, consultations for other conditions, and alongside other health checks at GPs.
default An adult hearing screening programme for 65 year olds would
default 
defaultensure people manage their hearing loss when they are most able to adapt.
default13.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA
defaultll health 
defaultand care 
defaultproviders should ensure 
defaultthat 
defaultstaff are trained in deaf awareness
default and communication tactics, that proper processes are in place for booking communication support, 
defaultthat assistive technologies are used 
defaultand that services are accessible
default to people with hearing loss and deafness
default.
default13.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultI
defaultnformation
default, guidance
default and 
defaulthealth promotion campaigns 
defaultaround other long-term conditions 
defaultshould be 
defaultprovided for 
defaultpeople with hearing loss and deaf people who use British Sign Language (BSL)
default in a format that they can access
default.
default13.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultD
defaultevelop better diagnostic tools, specialist services and guidance to support people with hearing loss who also have other long term conditions, and make sure these are used. 
defaultFor example, 
defaultaudiological
default assessments for people with dementia have been developed which simplify instructions
default, and some audiology departments have adapted their testing procedures so that they meet the needs of people with dementia. 
default13.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEnsure that resources are allocated in a cost effective way by properly managing hearing loss in people with other long term conditions. For example, the lack of resource allocated to hearing loss within the National Dementia Strategy for England should be reviewed.
